[[TITLE]] The Aster Documentation
[[TAGS]] aster doc documentation book howto explain
[[DESCRIPTION]] The description of the Aster documentation.

Aster is an extremely documented operating system. All of its source code is
completely available to anyone with an internet connection, and those lucky
folks are free to distribute it to those without one. There is also copious
amounts of in-system documentation for various functions, concepts, and even
whole books about designing systems for yourself. In order to accomplish this
widespread documentation, however, there are several rings Aster jumps through.

Firstly, there is the issue of getting the documentation into a proper format.
Not every system is the same, and not every user is the same, so we can't
necessarily store all required style information (italics, bolds, colors,
indents, etc.) in the documentation files themselves. To remedy this fact, it
was actually *nix that came up with a solution many years ago with the Roff
family of tools. Store little metasequences that have the desired effect
encoded, and the problem goes away. The problem with (G/T/N)Roff is that the
syntax is wholly unreadable. Getting into it as a non-veteran is very difficult,
and many are stumped by its strange acronyms when browsing through the
[[I;man/]] folder of their system.

Our solution to this problem is the Asterdoc format, a similar idea to Roff with
much easier-to-understand semantics and less unneeded features, as it's designed
specifically for documentation and nothing else. Writing an Asterdoc file is
very easy; You are REQUIRED to have only four things;

[[LIST]]
-- A title.
-- Some tags.
-- A description.
-- Contents.
[[ENDLIST]]

The title serves as a direct go-to when someone searches for your concept using
[[I;explain]]. The tags serve their purpose in the searching algorithm as
weights for ultimately the same purpose, providing a sorted list of what we
think the user is looking for. The description provides an explanation of the
page when it is in said list, so the user can confirm their search. The contents
are exactly that, contents. After the three aforementioned things are set in the
document, the contents are the rest of the page. The page contents can have
other tags within it to style things like code segments, lists, tables, and
more.

Asterdoc files are then added to the system via [[I;understand <astdoc-file>]].
That will copy the source code into the system's safekeeping area until it's
updated, and compile it into the binary blob used for getting these pages to the
output extremely quickly. If, for some reason, you need to regenerate that blob,
please see the [[REF;understand,manual page for the understand command]]. Usage
is detailed there.

A complete list of recognized Asterdoc tags are as follows;

[[LIST]]
-- [[TITLE]] The line title of the page, must only be specified once.
--| Format: [[TITLE]] <title>
-- [[TAGS]] A line of tags for the page, must only be specified once.
--| Format: [[TAGS]] <tag> <tag> <tag> ...
-- [[DESCRIPTION]] A line description for the page, must only be specified once.
--| Format: [[DESCRIPTION]] <description>
-- [[LIST]] A list of items.
--| Format: [[LIST]]
--| -- [[<item title (optional)> <item>
--| --| <item continuation>
--| -- ...
--| [[ENDLIST]]
-- [[SECTION]] A section within a table.
--| Format: [[SECTION]] <title>
--| -- [[<item title (optional)> <item>
--| --| <item continuation>
--| [[ENDSECTION]]
-- [[TABLE]] A table of items in sections.
--| Format: [[TABLE]]
--| [[SECTION]] <section>
--| [[ENDSECTION]]
--| ...
--| [[ENDTABLE]]
-- [[CODE]] A code snippet.
--| Format: [[CODE]] language
--| [[ENDCODE]]
-- [[REF]] A reference to another manual page.
--| Format: [[REF;<page>,<shown text>]]
-- [[SEEALSO]] A list of other useful manual pages for this topic.
--| Format: [[SEEALSO]]
--| -- [[REF;<page>,<title>]]
--| -- ...
--| [[ENDSEEALSO]]
-- [[I]] Italic text.
--| Format: [[I;<text>]]
-- [[B]] Bold text.
--| Format: [[B;<text>]]
-- [[HEADER]] A header marker.
--| Format: [[HEADER]] <text>
[[ENDLIST]]

Note that, when specifying one of these tags in the source file, it must be
enclosed in double brackets ([) on either side. If using Jasmine, syntax
highlighting and a basic LSP will guide you on which tags to use and how.
